07083nam a22010695i 9783110770186DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107701867 a10.1515/97831107701862doi  a(DE-B1597)611987  a(OCoLC)1340959441  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0110002bisacsh04a808.100aHow Language Speaks to Music :bProsody from a Cross-domain Perspective /ced. by Mathias Scharinger, Richard Wiese. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (V, 269 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistische Arbeiten ,x0344-6727 ;v58300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: How to conceptualize similarities between language and music -- tPitch units in music and speech prosody -- tMelody in speech and music -- tA constraint-based approach to structuring language and music: Towards a roadmap for comparing language and music cross-culturally -- tWord stress perception by congenital amusics -- tRhythmic structure – parallels between language and music -- tAlignment of prosodic weight and musical length in Finnish vocal music textsetting -- tMetrical mapping in text-setting: Empirical analysis and grammatical implementation -- tProminence alignment in English and Turkish songs: Implications for word prosodic typology -- tBridging speech and music – A neural common ground perspective on prosody -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProsody as a system of suprasegmental linguistic information such as rhythm and intonation is a prime candidate for looking at the relation between language and music in a principled way. This claim is based on several aspects: First, prosody is concerned with acoustic correlates of language and music that are directly comparable with each other by their physical properties such as duration and pitch. Second, prosodic accounts suggest a hierarchical organization of prosodic units that not only resembles a syntactic hierarchy, but is viewed as (part of) an interface to syntax. Third, prosody provides a very promising ground for evolutionary accounts of language and music. Fourth, bilateral transfer effects between language and music are best illustrated on the level of prosody. Highlighting the first two aspects, this book shows that it is a fruitful endeavor to use prosody for a principled comparison of language and music. In its broader sense, prosody as sound structure of communicative systems may be considered a »meta«-language that formalizes the way of "how music speaks to language and vice versa". Prosody is firmly established within linguistic theory, but is also applied in the musical domain. Therefore, prosody is not just a field of inquiry that shares elements or features between music and language, but can additionally provide a common conceptual ground.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMusic and language. 0aVersification. 4aMelodie. 4aMentale Repräsentation. 4aProsodische Hierarchie. 4aRhythmus. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Phonetics & Phonology.2bisacsh  aCognitive Representations.  aMelody.  aProsodic Hierarchy.  aRhythm.1 aArjava, Heini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbers, Dicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirardi, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamann, Silke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKabak, Barış, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKentner, Gerrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKotz, Sonja A., econtributor